    "summary": "Sappho (c. 630–570 BC) was the greatest lyric poet of ancient Greece — celebrated by later Greeks as the 'Tenth Muse' — who composed personal poetry of extraordinary emotional intensity about love, longing, desire, and the passage of time from the island of Lesbos. Her poems, written in the distinctive Sapphic meter she invented, survive primarily in quotations and fragments; a major papyrus discovery in 2014 added a nearly complete poem to the known corpus.\n\nSappho's work stands out in the ancient world for its unflinching subjectivity — she writes in the first person about her own emotional experiences, desires for women and men, and the pain of separation. Her fragment 31 (describing physical symptoms of jealousy while watching a beloved woman with a man) was analyzed by the philosopher Longinus as a supreme example of the sublime and influenced virtually every subsequent European poet who wrote about desire. The word 'lesbian' (from her island of Lesbos) and 'sapphic' derive from her. Ancient sources describe her as head of a thiasos — a circle of young women devoted to music, poetry, and the worship of Aphrodite — though the exact nature of these associations remains debated by scholars.",
